The truth of the matter is, there is no single point of failure in #Bitcoin, because of how truly decentralised the network is.

This decentralisation is due to the ease of running a Bitcoin node, which can be done on an old laptop.
@RolandStautz No better #Bitcoin than #Bitcoin
My node is also a Lightning node, which means it's used to route instant #Bitcoin payments on one of Bitcoin's layer 2s called the #LightningNetwork.
Every time I get sent #Bitcoin, my node checks to make sure that what I receive is actually Bitcoin, without me having to trust someone else's node to do that for me.

Each node checks every other node's copy of the #Bitcoin blockchain, to reach consensus on the current state of the ledger (who owns how much Bitcoin).

Any node that tries to change this ledger and give themselves some extra Bitcoin is automatically rejected and blacklisted.
Each node has a complete copy of the #Bitcoin blockchain, which it validates, from the beginning, based on the consensus rules of the Bitcoin protocol.
